@Reasoning
apply_dce_dead_function removes a single function identified by index into
the dead-functions list of wpa.dce_plan.

Bucket 0x0004 dispatches here. The DCEPlan struct's offset 0 is
dead_functions (a List of function IDs). For a single-candidate apply,
we look up the function ID, then iterate mir.functions to find and remove
it.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads wpa.dce_plan at WPA offset 128 (added by Layer 1 per design section
9). The dce_plan struct's offset 0 is dead_functions: a List of function
IDs. At the given index, retrieves the function ID, then removes the
matching function from mir.functions (offset 0, List).

Returns 1 on successful removal, 0 on no-op (index out of range, function
already removed, dce_plan not yet initialized).

Mirrors the per-function removal pattern from sweep_dead_functions
(line 1672 onward); the difference is that sweep_dead_functions iterates
the entire dead set, while this wrapper applies a single index from the
priority order.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(|mir.functions|) due to the linear scan to find the function ID.
Acceptable because priority-driven DCE typically processes a small number
of candidates (usually < 100 dead functions in a realistic build).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Removing a function that is actually reachable would produce a binary
with dangling call references. Soundness is guaranteed by WPA's reachability
analysis (per E3 hardening). This wrapper trusts the wpa.dce_plan input;
if the input is unsound, the output binary is unsound.
@End Security_Scope

