@Reasoning
apply_dce_dead_global removes a single global identified by index into the
dead-globals list of wpa.dce_plan.

Bucket 0x0005 dispatches here. dce_plan offset 16 is dead_globals (List of
global IDs). Global removal is more delicate than function removal because
the MIR's globals collection may be a Dictionary, a List, or another shape
- we use the conservative approach of marking the global as dead in the
CMO's optimization_stats Dict and letting sweep_dead_globals handle the
actual MIR mutation in a single bulk pass at the end.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads wpa.dce_plan at WPA offset 128, then dead_globals at DCEPlan offset
16. At the given index, retrieves the global ID. Records it in CMO's
optimization_stats with key "dead_global_<id>" semantics (we use the global
ID directly as the Dict key, value = 1).

The actual global removal from MIR is the responsibility of
sweep_dead_globals which is called at finalize_optimized_program time. The
priority-driven path's role is to record which globals to sweep, in priority
order, so any cascading optimizations (e.g. constant propagation that
depended on a now-dead global) see the order-of-operations correctly.

Returns 1 if the global ID was recorded, 0 if the index was out of range
or the dce_plan was not initialized.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1) Dictionary write. Sub-microsecond.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Same as apply_dce_dead_function: removing a referenced global produces
dangling references. Soundness is delegated to WPA.
@End Security_Scope

